    <body>
      <div xml:id="KT265-kilavi">
        <p type="edition">varaiyātu pirintaviṭattu “avar pirinta kāraṇa niṉṉai varaintu kōṭal
          kāraṇamākat tāṉ” eṉat tōḻi talaimakaṭkuk kūṟiyatu. </p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Spoken to HER by the confidante, saying “It [is] his
          separating that is [my] reason for thinking [that he will] marry you”, as he separated
          without marrying. </p>
      </div>

      <div xml:id="KT265">
        <lg type="edition">
          <l> kāntaḷaṅ koḻumukai kāval cellātu</l>
          <l> vaṇṭuvāy tiṟakkum poḻutiṟ paṇṭun</l>
          <l> tāmaṟi cemmaic cāṉṟōrk kaṇṭa</l>
          <l> kaṭaṉaṟi mākkaḷ pōla viṭaṉviṭ</l>
          <l> ṭitaḻtaḷai yaviḻnta vēkal veṟpa</l>
          <l> ṉaṉṉar neñcattaṉ ṟōḻi niṉṉilai</l>
          <l> yāṉṟaṉak kuraittaṉe ṉākat</l>
          <l> tāṉā ṇiṉaṉiḵ tākā vāṟē.</l>
        </lg>

        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
          <l>The man from the mountains of abundant stones, <note place="foot">
              <term xml:lang="ta"> ēkal</term> is, according to Cām., a noun meaning "height." (Cām.
            glosses <term xml:lang="ta">uyarcciyaiyuṭaiya</term>). But TL/DEDR know only <term xml:lang="ta">ēku-tal</term> "to go", and thus <term xml:lang="ta">ēkal</term>should
            be a verbal noun "going" (which is incomprehensible in the context). T.V.G., however,
            splits it as <term xml:lang="ta">ē kal</term> "abundant stones" (see DEDR 870 ē
            "abundance").</note>
          </l>
          <l rend="indent6">where petals have opened [their] bonds,</l>
          <l rend="indent">giving way <note place="foot">
              <term xml:lang="ta">iṭaṉ viṭṭu</term>: literally "having let go of the place" = not
            having resisted?</note> like people knowing [their] duty,</l>
          <l rend="indent">who have seen noble ones of an impartiality</l>
          <l rend="indent8">known to themselves, <note place="foot">What is the exact construction?
            What is the meaning of this comparison, which has to be connected with the petals?</note>
          </l>
          <l rend="indent3">even before, at a time when bees open [their] mouths,</l>
          <l rend="indent3">unguardable <note place="foot">For the construction of verbal noun + <term xml:lang="ta">cellā(tu)</term> see KT 159.1, 287.4, 340.3.</note> , on the rich buds
            of the Malabar lily,</l>
          <l>he has a good heart, friend. <note place="foot">Probably here his good heart refers to
            his having proper intentions (namely of marrying her), for which KT 259.8 is perhaps a
            parallel.</note>
          </l>
          <l rend="indent2">When I told him about your state</l>
          <l>he himself was ashamed: “this is no way.”</l>


        </lg>
      </div>
